Anki

<span key="9ba07248598c40819dec28e7f9ae5c7e"><span offset-key="9ba07248598c40819dec28e7f9ae5c7e:0">Anki is an awesome app that uses </span></span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spaced_repetition" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="65c9ebff44c64076a48e8802f2b67343" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-46333_259-46334-237__"><span data-key="66a926c07e1245178fb0e4348d301dca"><span data-offset-key="66a926c07e1245178fb0e4348d301dca:0">spaced repetition learning</span></span></span></a><span key="a21f3ce33e634acb8ea3c988aceae1b3"><span offset-key="a21f3ce33e634acb8ea3c988aceae1b3:0"> to memorize and learn things efficiently.</span></span>

<span key="14e34e5ff6a5483399bafb0395a66689"><span offset-key="14e34e5ff6a5483399bafb0395a66689:0">The reason I am not currently using it is because I find the philosophy of </span>`Knowing something is knowing where it is written down.`<span offset-key="14e34e5ff6a5483399bafb0395a66689:2"> much more effective than memorizing things. And I am pretty fast on the computer already so looking something up is 'nearly' as fast as retrieving something from memory. Also I believe that doing something that you want to get good at a lot of times is the only real way to learn and master anything. That said, Anki is pretty great for learning vocabulary for a language as that is something where memorization and 'knowing' some thing is actually important. But even then being immersed in the environment where you try to speak the language is much more effective.</span></span>

> <span key="db9b647450484dfd81097b242114816c"><span offset-key="db9b647450484dfd81097b242114816c:0">A language isnâ€™t something you learn so much as something you join.</span></span>

<span key="08942be91a2440a0ba400fbca1c59c7b"><span offset-key="08942be91a2440a0ba400fbca1c59c7b:0">Tips</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="e79158cbfe8c4c0593382f1613564027"><span offset-key="e79158cbfe8c4c0593382f1613564027:0">Review all cards every day, not just one topic. Ensure that you're not hitting the "Review limit" on a deck.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="247efda60076463aada041ce40441adb"><span offset-key="247efda60076463aada041ce40441adb:0">Use tags: Tag all cards that are more likely to appear on your exam and review them more often.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="caee3ccc98fb448c8dd8e9370e28fcb0"><span offset-key="caee3ccc98fb448c8dd8e9370e28fcb0:0">Use Lapses: if you fail a card n times, then let it be suspended and work on rewording it.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="36d1c024cf3f4d608ba0ee98703a0953"><span offset-key="36d1c024cf3f4d608ba0ee98703a0953:0">Reduce the amount of time spend on cards. If you do not have near-instant recall, mark it as "Again" and spend more time learning.</span></span>
